snippet.textDisplay:
Diongenes was a wise man, he found pleasure in simple things by renunciation and delaying gratification. It's an art of finding pleasure through suffering. We're primed to run away from pain and overindulge in pleasure until it loses all meaning, we become numb, desensitized and empty by overindulgence, but strife against the imposed current of status quo is essential to our spiritual growth. To truly become a spiritually strong individual, one must battle against the world of misconception and indoctrination. Thinking fame and wealth brings happiness is the biggest lie in history of humankind. When Alexander the Great said he'll give him anything he wants, Diogenes replied: "Get out of my sun." Be careful what you wish for, the idea might sound great in your head but what about your hearts "true will" the aspect of spiritual nature which transcends impermanence of body, which is almost forgotten in modern age. People get so lost in pursuit of fame and fortune only to find themselves in a hollow place, on the outside they might seem satisfied by their achievements, but that's only a mirage of transience, linear time passing them by, in fact they're the most unhappy individuals to roam the earth, always feeling the hunger of "true will", but filling the void with the wrong things, illusions of time, the "matrix". You can't serve two masters, by serving one you'll offend the other. You are both of these masters, one represents "free will" (ego of linear time) the other "true will" (transcends time and space) of higher self.
In Gospel of Thomas Jesus said: "The Father's kingdom is like a merchant who had a supply of merchandise and found a pearl. That merchant was prudent; he sold the merchandise and bought the single pearl for himself. So also with you, seek this treasure that is unfailing, that is enduring, where no moth comes to eat and no worm destroys. Anyone here with two ears had better listen!
